"1325","1401":"1401","1477":"1477","1367":"1367","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1342":"1342","1409":"1409","about 1386":"omkring 1386","1416":"1416","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1365–1404":"1365–1404","1342–1401":"1342–1401","1352–Male":"1352–Overleden","1367–1409":"1367–1409","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1388–1416":"1388–1416","1327–1395":"1327–1395","1325–1365":"1325–1365","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","14 February 1395":"14 februari 1395","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","Abt 1340":"circa 1340","1327":"1327","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1477":"1477","1367":"1367","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1342":"1342","1409":"1409","about 1386":"circa 1386","1416":"1416","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1365–1404":"1365–1404","1342–1401":"1342–1401","1352–Male":"1352–Deceased","1367–1409":"1367–1409","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1388–1416":"1388–1416","1327–1395":"1327–1395","1325–1365":"1325–1365","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","14 February 1395":"14 February 1395","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","Abt 1340":"about 1340","1327":"1327","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1477":"1477","1367":"1367","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1342":"1342","1409":"1409","about 1386":"about 1386","1416":"1416","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beeston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of the many places in England so called. Those in Nottinghamshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire were settlements where bent grass grew (Old English <i>bēos</i> ‘rough grass’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’). In Bedfordshire it probably denoted a settlement on a bend (Old English <i>byge</i> + genitive singular <i>-es</i> + <i>tūn</i>). The hamlet stands on a marked bend of the river Yvel. In Cheshire it is named from a rock, below which trading took place (Old English <i>byge</i> ‘commerce’ + Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’). The reference is to a prominent crag where the remains of Beeston Castle stand. Compare   Beaston   and   Beeson  .","occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived in that part of a village known in Middle English as <i>bi este toun</i> ‘(place) at the east (end) of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   and   Beaston  ."]},{"name":"Beeson","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston  , a habitational name from a place called Beeston. The spelling reflects the local pronunciation of the Nottinghamshire placename, although this form is now quite widespread in England."]},{"name":"Beaston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   (the more common form of the surname in England), a habitational name from any of various places called Beeston."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":17,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Thomas Beeston was born in 1365, in Beeston, Cheshire, England, his father, Henry de Beeston, was 38 and his mother, Matilda Thornton, was 41. He married Margaret T Jesson about 1386, in Peover Superior, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1404, in Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1365–1404":"1365–1404","1342–1401":"1342–1401","1352–Male":"1352–Surnud","1367–1409":"1367–1409","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1388–1416":"1388–1416","1327–1395":"1327–1395","1325–1365":"1325–1365","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","14 February 1395":"14. veebruar 1395","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","Abt 1340":"umbes 1340","1327":"1327","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1477":"1477","1367":"1367","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1342":"1342","1409":"1409","about 1386":"umbes 1386","1416":"1416","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1365–1404":"1365–1404","1342–1401":"1342–1401","1352–Male":"1352–Kuollut","1367–1409":"1367–1409","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1388–1416":"1388–1416","1327–1395":"1327–1395","1325–1365":"1325–1365","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","14 February 1395":"14. helmikuuta 1395","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","Abt 1340":"noin 1340","1327":"1327","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1477":"1477","1367":"1367","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1342":"1342","1